Mechanics of Materials Chapter3

## 3.2 Torsional Deformations of a Circular Bar

- assumption; small angle twist

![_config.yml](/images/MechanicsOfMaterials/torsion_figure1.png)

$$
\gamma = \rho d\phi / dx = \rho \theta = {\rho\over r}\gamma_\text{max}\\
 \text{from} \quad \gamma dx = \rho d\phi
$$

- shear strain proportionally increase with radius
- $d\phi/dx$ is called __rate of twist__; angle of twist per unit length

## 3.3 Circular Bars of Linearly Elastic Materials

![_config.yml](/images/MechanicsOfMaterials/torsion_figure2.png)

- use Hooke's Law

$$
\tau = G\gamma = G\rho\theta = G\rho\phi/dx = {\rho\over r} \tau _\text{max}
$$

- for out-surface values, $\rho$ would be maximum value; $r$

__The Torsion Formula__

![_config.yml](/images/MechanicsOfMaterials/torsion_figure3.png)

moment at small area

$$
dM = \tau\rho\,dA = {\tau_\text{max} \over r} \rho^2\,dA
$$

integral over entire cross-sectional area

$$
T = \int_A dM = {\tau_\text{max}\over r} \int_A\rho^2\,dA = {\tau_\text{max} \over r} I_P
$$

- $I_P$ is called __poliar moment of inertia__

shear stress on the surface by torsion

$$
\tau_\text{max} = {Tr\over I_P}
$$

__Angle of Twist__

$$
\theta = {d\phi \over dx} = {T\over G I_P}
\\

\because \quad \tau / G\rho = \gamma/\rho =  \theta = {T\over G I_P}
$$

- also able to define __torsional stiffness__

$$
k_T = {GI_P\over L} \quad | \quad k={EA\over L}
$$


## 3.5 Stresses and Strains in Pure Shear

![_config.yml](/images/MechanicsOfMaterials/torsion_figure4.png)

$$
\sigma_\theta  = \tau \sin 2\theta \quad \tau_\theta = \tau \cos 2 \theta
$$

- stress elements oriented at $\theta = 0\ \text{or} \ \theta = 45\quad \text{[DEG]}$

__Strains in Pure Shear__

$$
\epsilon_\text{max} = {\tau\over E} + {\nu\tau \over E} = {\tau\over E}(1+\nu) \quad \text{at}\ \theta = 45
$$

